      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my bathroom sink is dripping constantly and i cant figure out why. it's a regular faucet i think so it doesnt have a cartridge or anything? what do i need to fix it and how do i go about replacing the part that's leaking?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A regular faucet dripping constantly is usually a sign that the internal \"globe\" or \"ball\" mechanism inside the valve has lost its grip on the water stream, much like a goblin who has forgotten how to hold a cup of water. It's a very common issue, and while you don't need to replace a cartridge (that's for the fancy, high-tech ones), you might need to replace the internal ball or the washer, which is often the part that needs swapping.\n\nTo fix it, you'll need a wrench, a bucket to catch the water, and a little bit of patience, because the water will be spraying everywhere until you get the ball back in place. First, turn off the water supply to the sink, then use a wrench to loosen the nut on the bottom of the faucet handle. Once the handle is off, you can see the internal mechanism. If the ball is stuck, you might need to use a small screwdriver to gently wiggle it back into position, or you might need to replace the washer underneath it.\n\nIf you're not comfortable doing this yourself, you can call a plumber, but if you want to try, just remember that the goblin inside the faucet is usually just a",
